Merchant
Role
Merchants own buying strategy for the business. Merchants read the market, competitor bids, freight, and plant needs to decide how aggressively to price while managing position — balancing what the business has bought, sold, and still needs to cover. They turn that into direction for Originators so grain keeps flowing without overpaying or putting margin at risk.
Primary goals
•	Keep plants covered without giving away margin
•	Read the competitive landscape quickly
•	Turn market judgment into actionable field direction
•	Monitor whether strategy is working
What matters most
•	Stay competitive without overbidding
•	Keep plants covered
•	Give originators named accounts and price direction
•	See quickly if yesterday’s strategy worked
What they do
•	Assess market position and competitor behavior
•	Set bid floors, spreads, and pricing posture
•	Build/refine target producer lists
•	Package guidance for originators
•	Review outcomes and decide whether to adjust
What they need
•	Fast view of the market and competitive landscape
•	Clear path from analysis to target list
•	Easy delivery of actionable guidance to originators
•	Simple feedback loop on what worked yesterday
Pain points
•	Rebuilds the same scenario over and over instead of starting from saved defaults
•	Has to manually add or adjust competitors to reflect the real market (data can be inaccurate)
•	Hover / inspect behavior gets in the way of lassoing and map selection
•	Exports to spreadsheet to clean columns, filter lists, and package for originators
•	Uses contract advisee emails and inbox traffic to piece together outcomes
•	Falls back to screenshots, email, or verbal direction when using the tool is slower than routing around it
Current workarounds
•	Exporting and reformatting spreadsheets
•	Sending screenshots, emails, and verbal guidance
•	Using inbox activity to infer outcomes
•	Falling back to ad hoc judgment when the workflow is too painful
Tools
•	Strategic pricing tool 
•	Excel / local spreadsheets
o	Bid sheet
o	Stox report
o	Freight sheet
o	Position sheet
•	Teams
•	Email
•	Lynx
•	ProfitX
•	Phone / texting
•	Screenshots / manual workarounds
Opportunity
Make the tool a true merchant workbench:
•	Save default facility / month / competitor setups so daily analysis starts faster
•	Give merchants a table view after the map so they can sort, filter, and package lists without Excel
•	Show “what happened yesterday” in one place instead of making merchants read email to infer results
•	Create originator-ready outputs directly in the tool instead of after-the-fact spreadsheet cleanup
 
Distinctions: Ben vs. Jonathan
	Ben	Jonathan
Core use	Daily competitive landscape scan	Weekly strategy + originator direction
What he values	Quick read on competitor position	Turning strategy into team action
Main pain	Tool is useful but not intuitive	Workflow breaks once he has to export and distribute
What he wants	Keep the logic, make it easier to use	Saved defaults, easier setup, clearer prior-day feedback
Operating context	Market reading and bid logic	Crush plant coverage and team coordination
